        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "I've spent some time running through the code with a debugger investigating this issue and have hit a wall in my understanding. If someone has insight into how libuv sets up `stdin` and how fish is different, I'd love to receive some pointers on where to look next.\r\n\r\nI've simplified the example to `system(\"cat\", \"1\")`. The input needs at least one byte since an empty input has a fast path. The string argument ensures the command is called with the configured `shell`, so this issue appears to be specifically with `fish -c cat`. The issue doesn't occur with the shell set to `bash`, `zsh`, or `sh`. \r\n\r\nI haven't managed to reproduce this outside of neovim, so I suspect that fish has a non-standard expectation for how stdin needs to be setup in libuv. \r\n\r\nAs a workaround, I've set my neovim shell to `bash` for now",
